<p>Wisconsin's continental climate demands HVAC systems capable of handling extreme temperature variations, from summer highs in the 80s-90s¬∞F to winter lows often reaching -10¬∞F or below. Heating requirements dominate energy consumption, with most homes requiring 6-8 months of heating annually. The heating degree days average around 7,000-8,000 statewide, while cooling degree days range from 600-900, indicating that heating efficiency should be the primary consideration when selecting HVAC equipment.</p>

<p>For air conditioning systems, SEER ratings of 14-16 provide optimal efficiency without over-investing in cooling capacity that sees limited use. However, proper humidity control during Wisconsin's humid summers is crucial for comfort and indoor air quality. Heat pumps are becoming increasingly viable for Wisconsin homes, particularly newer cold-climate models that maintain efficiency down to -10¬∞F or lower. Traditional furnace systems remain popular, with high-efficiency models achieving AFUE ratings of 90-98%, while boiler systems work well in older homes with existing radiator or radiant floor systems.</p>

