<h2>Wisconsin Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Wisconsin homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC investments. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) remains the most substantial incentive, allowing homeowners to deduct 30% of solar installation costs from their federal taxes through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and even energy storage systems. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this represents \$6,000 in direct tax savings.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available through 2032, this credit covers solar panels, inverters, mounting equipment, installation labor, and energy storage systems. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability, and there's no maximum limit on the credit amount.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Wisconsin law exempts the added value of renewable energy systems from property tax assessments, ensuring that solar installations won't increase property tax bills despite adding significant home value.</li>
<li><strong>We Energies Rebates:</strong> We Energies offers rebates up to \$1,200 for ENERGY STAR certified central air conditioning systems, \$600-1,000 for high-efficiency furnaces, and up to \$1,800 for qualifying heat pump installations. Solar customers benefit from net metering programs that credit excess production at retail rates.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Many municipal utilities throughout Wisconsin offer additional rebates and financing programs. Madison Gas & Electric provides solar rebates and HVAC efficiency incentives, while Wisconsin Public Service offers comprehensive energy efficiency programs with substantial rebates.</li>
<li><strong>Financing Options:</strong> Wisconsin homeowners can access solar loans with rates as low as 2.99-6.99%, while PACE financing programs in select counties allow property tax-based repayment for energy improvements. Many utilities also offer on-bill financing for HVAC upgrades.</li>
</ul>

